04949nam a22006615i 9780887555374DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875553747 a10.1515/97808875553742doi  a(DE-B1597)664653  a(OCoLC)1408681347  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 7aMED0390002bisacsh04a362.2/10971242231 aDyck, Erika, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aManaging Madness :bWeyburn Mental Hospital and the Transformation of Psychiatric Care in Canada /cErika Dyck, Alex Deighton. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tNote on Photographs -- tAcknowledgements -- tWho has Seen the Asylum? -- tOptimism and Celebration -- tExperiencing the Asylum -- tFalse Starts -- tSocializing Mental Health Care -- tPills, Politics, and Experiments of All Kinds -- tDissolving the Walls -- tHospital Diasporas -- tConsumption And Survival -- tLegacies -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Saskatchewan Mental Hospital at Weyburn has played a significant role in the history of psychiatric services, mental health research, and providing care in the community. Its history provides a window to the changing nature of mental health services over the 20th century. Built in 1921, Saskatchewan Mental Hospital was considered the last asylum in North America and the largest facility of its kind in the British Commonwealth. A decade later the Canadian Committee for Mental Hygiene cited it as one of the worst facilities in the country, largely due to extreme overcrowding. In the 1950s the Saskatchewan Mental Hospital again attracted international attention for engaging in controversial therapeutic interventions, including treatments using LSD. In the 1960s, sweeping healthcare reforms took hold in the province and mental health institutions underwent dramatic changes as they began transferring patients into communities. As the patient and staff population shrunk, the once palatial building fell into disrepair, the asylum’s expansive farmland went out of cultivation, and mental health services folded into a complicated web of social and correctional services. Erika Dyck’s Managing Madness examines an institution that housed people we struggle to understand, help, or even try to change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMental health serviceszSaskatchewanxHistory. 0aMental health services-Saskatchewan-History. 0aMentally illxInstitutional carezSaskatchewanxHistory. 0aMentally ill-Institutional care-Saskatchewan-History. 0aPsychiatric hospitalszSaskatchewanxHistory. 0aPsychiatric hospitals-Saskatchewan-History. 0aSaskatchewan Hospital (Weyburn, Sask.). 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh1 aDeighton, Alex, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDyck, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElias, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerber, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLafave, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMills, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, Tracey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi